subSubSection.paragraph:
As reported by 
McCallum & Poore (2013: fig. 1C)
for the north-western Australian material, the present specimen also has small scattered spines on the surface of thoracic sternite 4 (
Fig. 2B
), which are not illustrated by 
Baba (1988: fig. 5b)
. The antennal scale is present but rudimentary (
Fig. 2C, D
) as described by 
Baba (1988)
and 
McCallum & Poore (2013)
for the Philippine and north-western Australian specimens. The antennal article 5 is approximately two times longer than the article 4 and reaches to the midlength of the antennular penultimate article (
Fig. 2C, D
). The external appearance and armature of the P1–4 are generally similar to those of the previous illustrations (
Fig. 1B, E, F
; 
Alcock & Anderson 1899b
: pl. 45, fig. 1; 
Alcock & McArdle 1902
: pl. 58, fig. 4; 
McCallum & Poore 2013
: fig. 1G, H).
